title: Divide Among Supreme Court’s Conservatives Could Test Trump’s Agenda
partialText: In rejecting President Trump’s tariffs, the court’s six conservative justices displayed subtle differences in their views of executive power.

title: ‘Murky Waters’ for Global Businesses After Trump’s Tariff Loss
partialText: Even after the Supreme Court invalidated many of the president’s levies, foreign leaders and executives assume that U.S. tariffs are here to stay, in one form or another.

title: Trump Doubles Down on Closing Tax Loophole on Cheap Imports
partialText: The exemption was shut down last year by President Trump based, in part, on the same legal grounds as the tariffs that were invalidated by the Supreme Court.

title: Bench Presses, Pull Ups … Kid Rock? The White House Had a Very Manly Week.
partialText: President Trump’s top cabinet officials are pumping iron in public.

title: Bridge Owner Donated $1 Million to MAGA Group Before Trump Blasted Competitor
partialText: The PAC and the White House say the donation had nothing to do with President Trump’s tirade against a new bridge connecting Detroit and Windsor, Ontario.

title: Longtime Virginia Lawyer Chosen by Judges as U.S. Attorney, and Then Fired
partialText: It was the second time this month that the administration had gotten rid of a top federal prosecutor appointed to his post by federal judges.

title: Judge Rebukes U.S. Over Application to Search Washington Post Reporter’s Home
partialText: A prosecutor apologized for failing to alert the magistrate to a 1980 law that restricts searches for reporting materials.

title: Why Attacking Iran Could Be Riskier Than Capturing Maduro
partialText: Iran’s extensive military abilities and network of regional proxies could draw the United States into a prolonged conflict.

title: U.S. Planes Land at Jordan Base, a Key Hub for Planning Possible Iran Strikes
partialText: At least 60 attack aircraft are parked at the base, which has become a key hub for U.S. military planning for possible strikes on Iran.

title: How Johannes Klaebo’s 6 Gold Medals Ranks Among the All-Time Olympic Performances
partialText: The Norwegian cross-country skier completed the biggest medal haul ever by an athlete at a Winter Games, and one of the biggest at any single Olympics.

title: Los Angeles Olympics Have a Cloud of Concerns as Winter Games Close
partialText: New details about the LA28 chairman’s ties to Jeffrey Epstein, as well as anxiety over key infrastructure projects, have thrown the planning into disarray.

title: He Researched Dishonesty. He Got Friendly With Jeffrey Epstein.
partialText: Dan Ariely, a behavioral scientist at Duke, sought out the convicted sex offender for his research. Their yearslong correspondence suggests it wasn’t all business.

title: Shocker! SCOTUS Schools POTUS
partialText: The high court asserts itself as tariff sheriff.

title: Epstein Was Only One of Thousands of Traffickers in the U.S.
partialText: Every year, more than 100,000 children may be sold for sex in the United States. Are we willing to do something about that?

title: Future Perfect
partialText: Does taking care of our future selves have to mean sacrifice in the present?

title: Blizzard Warnings Issued for Swath of East Coast, Including N.Y.C.
partialText: The blizzard warnings are the first since 2017 for New York City, which is expected to get up to 18 inches of snow, or more.

title: How $600 Drones Are Outsmarting Colombia’s Billion-Dollar Military
partialText: Security officials say easy access by guerrilla groups to commercial drones, cheaply modified into deadly weapons, has put the nation’s army on its heels.

title: At A.I. Summit, India Tries to Find a Way Between the U.S. and China
partialText: India is using technology as a tool of foreign policy, casting itself as a moral voice for smaller, developing countries.

title: Ruben Ray Martinez Was Killed in an Undisclosed ICE Shooting in March, His Family Says
partialText: A 23-year-old American was shot last March in South Padre Island. ICE’s involvement in the shooting was not disclosed until this week.
